If you accepted receive-since, you could always
refer to a particular message-id.  I just think
either version violates the opacity of URLs.

The problem with using POST or DELETE is that the
server now has to maintain read state for each
client and you now have an administrative process
each time you add a client.

-Alex-

On Tue, 7 Jan 2003, Seairth Jacobs wrote:

&gt; Using something like &quot;receive-since&quot; (I am assuming a timestamp here) means
&gt; that you have to keep track of the time differences between the client and
&gt; server, since you need to query the server according to its own time, not
&gt; the clients.
&gt;
&gt; I think you would do better to have an &quot;inbox&quot; URI, which only contains new
&gt; messages.  Once you have received a specific message (indicated via the
&gt; inbox), POST its URI to the URI of the mail resource you want it to be put
&gt; in:
&gt;
&gt; POST /mail/trash
&gt;
&gt; http://sample.invalid/mail/inbox/0013
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; This would remove the link from the inbox and place it in the &quot;trash&quot;.  Of
&gt; course, you could always just DELETE the URI directly if you were done with
&gt; it.
&gt;
&gt; At any rate, all you would ever have to do to check for mail would be to
&gt; &quot;GET /mail/inbox&quot;.
&gt;
&gt; Simple and clean... I think.  :)
&gt;
